<section id="methodology">
  <details>
    <summary>Index Methodology &amp; Assumptions</summary>
    <div class="meth-body">

      <div>
        <h3>Overview</h3>
        <p>The Debt Sustainability Index (DSI) scores each country from 0 to 100 based on five World Bank indicators covering debt stock, fiscal flows, external exposure, and growth dynamics. A higher score indicates greater debt sustainability and more fiscal space. The framework approximates — in simplified, backward-looking form — the conceptual underpinning of the IMF/World Bank Debt Sustainability Framework (DSF) for low-income countries.</p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3>Component Indicators &amp; Weights</h3>
        <table class="meth-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Component</th><th>World Bank Code</th><th>Weight</th><th>Rationale</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Government Debt / GDP</td>
              <td>GC.DOD.TOTL.GD.ZS</td>
              <td>30%</td>
              <td>Primary solvency signal; total central government obligations relative to output.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Interest / Revenue</td>
              <td>GC.INT.TOTL.RV.ZS</td>
              <td>25%</td>
              <td>Measures the fiscal squeeze: what share of every dollar collected is consumed by debt service, crowding out public spending.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Fiscal Balance / GDP</td>
              <td>GC.BAL.CASH.GD.ZS</td>
              <td>20%</td>
              <td>Flow measure of trajectory — persistent deficits compound the debt stock; a surplus signals room to manoeuvre.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>External Debt / GNI</td>
              <td>DT.DOD.DECT.GD.ZS</td>
              <td>15%</td>
              <td>External vulnerability; captures exposure to exchange-rate and refinancing risk from foreign-currency obligations.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>GDP Growth</td>
              <td>NY.GDP.MKTP.KD.ZG</td>
              <td>10%</td>
              <td>Growth reduces the debt/GDP ratio mechanically and expands the revenue base. A positive growth–interest-rate differential is the core of debt sustainability arithmetic.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3>Scoring Thresholds</h3>
        <p>Each indicator is converted to a 0–100 sub-score using piecewise linear interpolation between breakpoints informed by IMF DSF thresholds for low-income countries. Scores outside the outer breakpoints are capped at 0 or 100.</p>
        <table class="meth-table" style="margin-top:0.6rem">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Component</th><th>Score 100</th><th>Score 70</th><th>Score 30</th><th>Score 0</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Debt / GDP</td><td>≤ 0%</td><td>30%</td><td>55%</td><td>≥ 80%</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Interest / Revenue</td><td>0%</td><td>10%</td><td>22.5%</td><td>≥ 35%</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Fiscal Balance / GDP</td><td>≥ +5%</td><td>0%</td><td>−5%</td><td>≤ −10%</td></tr>
            <tr><td>External Debt / GNI</td><td>≤ 0%</td><td>30%</td><td>55%</td><td>≥ 80%</td></tr>
            <tr><td>GDP Growth</td><td>≥ 7%</td><td>4%</td><td>0%</td><td>≤ −5%</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p style="margin-top:0.5rem">The 30% / 55% debt thresholds correspond to IMF DSF low/high-risk boundaries for weak and medium policy-and-institutional environments respectively. The 10% / 22.5% interest-to-revenue thresholds are drawn from IMF DSF present-value debt-service benchmarks.</p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3>Risk Categories</h3>
        <table class="meth-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Score</th><th>Category</th><th>IMF DSF analogue</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>75–100</td><td style="color:#68d391">Low risk</td><td>Low risk of debt distress</td></tr>
            <tr><td>50–74</td><td style="color:#f6e05e">Moderate risk</td><td>Moderate risk</td></tr>
            <tr><td>25–49</td><td style="color:#fbd38d">High risk</td><td>High risk</td></tr>
            <tr><td>0–24</td><td style="color:#fc8181">Very high risk</td><td>In or near debt distress</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3>Assumptions &amp; Caveats</h3>
        <ul class="caveat-list">
          <li><strong>Central government only.</strong> The debt indicator covers central government and typically excludes state-owned enterprise liabilities, sub-national borrowing, and explicitly guaranteed debt. True public sector exposures are often materially higher.</li>
          <li><strong>Historical data, not forward-looking.</strong> The IMF/World Bank DSF uses projections and stress tests over a 20-year horizon. This index is entirely backward-looking, using the most recent year with available data. It does not capture anticipated fiscal consolidation, commodity windfalls, or ongoing debt restructurings.</li>
          <li><strong>Data gaps and lags.</strong> Several countries — including Eritrea, Somalia, South Sudan, and Sudan — have limited or no recent data for one or more indicators. Countries with data covering less than 30% of composite weight are excluded. Where data is partial, scores are renormalised across available components and flagged in the detail panel.</li>
          <li><strong>Mixed data vintages.</strong> Each indicator uses its most recent available year, which varies by country and indicator. Fiscal balance and revenue data frequently lag by 2–3 years, meaning comparisons across countries may implicitly compare different time periods.</li>
          <li><strong>Weights are illustrative.</strong> The 30/25/20/15/10 weighting reflects a reasonable professional judgement about relative importance but is not derived from a formal econometric or Bayesian model. Alternative weighting schemes can produce notably different rankings.</li>
          <li><strong>Off-budget and hidden debt.</strong> IMF analysis (2019–2023) has identified significant underreporting in several African countries, particularly from bilateral lending recorded off-budget. This index cannot capture what is not reported to the World Bank.</li>
          <li><strong>Not investment advice.</strong> This visualisation is for illustrative and educational purposes only. It does not constitute investment advice or substitute for country-specific debt sustainability analyses conducted by the IMF, World Bank, or professional credit analysts.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

    </div>
  </details>
</section>

